━━ YOUR TASK ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Canonicalize the merged list.  Do NOT re-extract names — only reorganise
what is already present.

Canonicalization rules
──────────────────────
1.  Identify entries that represent the **same character** but differ due to:
    •  Same-phonetic variants (同音字): e.g. "货建华" vs "霍建华"
    •  OCR misreads: e.g. "豁" vs "霍", "0" vs "O" in English names
    •  Abbreviated vs full names treated as separate entries
    •  Different romanisation conventions for the same name
2.  Merge all such entries under the single **most formal, most complete, or
    most frequently occurring** canonical form.
3.  Add every merged variant as an alias (including the discarded canonical).
4.  Union all alias and ocr_en_variants lists.
5.  Remove entries that appear to be **incidental** (very few aliases, clearly
    not a character name — e.g. location names or random nouns).
6.  Every entry in the output MUST include the "canonical" field.

━━ OUTPUT FORMAT ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Return ONLY the following JSON — no prose, no code fences, no commentary:

{
  "characters": {
    "<canonical_zh>": {
      "canonical": "<canonical_zh>",
      "aliases": ["<every_variant_including_merged_duplicates>"],
      "canonical_en": "<English_name_or_null>",
      "ocr_en_variants": ["<ocr_typo_1>", "<variant_2>"]
    }
  }
}

